[src:attrs-classes/examples] `attrs.fields()` will raise an `AttributeError` when the field doesn’t exist while literal string names won’t.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] Using `attrs.fields()` to get attributes is worth being recommended in most cases.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] For more advanced transformations and conversions, we recommend you look at a companion library (such as *cattrs*).
[src:attrs-classes/examples] Sometimes you want to have default values for your initializer.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] And sometimes you even want mutable objects as default values (ever accidentally used `def f(arg=[])`?).
[src:attrs-classes/examples] More information on why class methods for constructing objects are awesome can be found in this insightful blog post.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] Default factories can also be set using the `factory` argument to `field()`, and using a decorator.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] Please keep in mind that the decorator approach *only* works if the attribute in question has a `field()` assigned to it.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] As a result, annotating an attribute with a type is *not* enough if you use `@default`.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] Although your initializers should do as little as possible (ideally: just initialize your instance according to the arguments!), it can come in handy to do some kind of validation on the arguments.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] Please note that the decorator approach only works if – and only if! – the attribute in question has a `field()` assigned.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] Therefore if you use `@validator`, it is *not* enough to annotate said attribute with a type.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] If using the old-school `attr.s()` decorator, validators only run on initialization by default.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] If using the newer `attrs.define()` and friends, validators run on initialization *and* on attribute setting.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] This behavior can be changed using the *on_setattr* argument.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] Attributes can have a `converter` function specified, which will be called with the attribute’s passed-in value to get a new value to use.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] This can be useful for doing type-conversions on values that you don’t want to force your callers to do.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] If using the old-school `attr.s()` decorator, converters only run on initialization by default.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] If using the newer `attrs.define()` and friends, converters run on initialization *and* on attribute setting.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] The generated `__init__` method will have an attribute called `__annotations__` that contains this type information.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] If your annotations contain strings (for example, forward references), you can resolve these after all references have been defined by using `attrs.resolve_types()`.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] This will replace the *type* attribute in the respective fields.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] If you find yourself using string type annotations to handle forward references, wrap the entire type annotation in quotes instead of only the type you need a forward reference to (so `'list[A]'` instead of `list['A']`).
[src:attrs-classes/examples] This is a limitation of the Python typing system.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] Slotted classes have several advantages on CPython.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] `define()` sets `slots=True` by default.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] Sometimes you have instances that shouldn’t be changed after instantiation.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] Immutability is especially popular in functional programming and is generally a very good thing.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] Please note that true immutability is impossible in Python but it will get you 99% there.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] By themselves, immutable classes are useful for long-lived objects that should never change; like configurations for example.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] In order to use them in regular program flow, you’ll need a way to easily create new instances with changed attributes.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] Sometimes you may want to create a class programmatically.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] Sometimes, you want to have your class’s `__init__` method do more than just the initialization, validation, etc. that gets done for you automatically when using `@define`.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] To do this, just define a `__attrs_post_init__` method in your class.
[src:attrs-classes/examples] It will get called at the end of the generated `__init__` method.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] In data hierarchy, a **field** (**data field**) is a variable in a record.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] A record, also known as a data structure, allows logically related data to be identified by a single name.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] Identifying related data as a single group is central to the construction of understandable computer programs.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] The individual fields in a record may be accessed by name, just like any variable in a computer program.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] Each field in a record has two components.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] One component is the field's datatype declaration.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] The other component is the field's identifier.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] Fields may be stored in random access memory (RAM).
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] The following Pascal record definition has three field identifiers: firstName, lastName, and age.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] The two name fields have a datatype of an array of character.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] The age field has a datatype of integer.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] In Pascal, the identifier component precedes a colon, and the datatype component follows the colon.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] Once a record is defined, variables of the record can be allocated.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] Once the memory of the record is allocated, a field can be accessed like a variable by using the dot notation.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] Over time, the term *field* has been replaced with the terms *data member* and *attribute*.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] The following Java class has three attributes: firstName, lastName, and age.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] Fields may be stored in a random access file.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] A file may be written to or read from in an arbitrary order.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] To accomplish the arbitrary access, the operating system provides a method to quickly *seek* around the file.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] Once the disk head is positioned at the beginning of a record, each file field can be read into its corresponding memory field.
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] File fields are the main storage structure in the Indexed Sequential Access Method (ISAM).
[src:attrs-classes/field-computer-science] In relational database theory, the term *field* has been replaced with the terms *column* and *attribute*.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In object-oriented (OO) and functional programming, an **immutable object** (unchangeable object) is an object whose state cannot be modified after it is created.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] This is in contrast to a **mutable object** (changeable object), which can be modified after it is created.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In some cases, an object is considered immutable even if some internally used attributes change, but the object's state appears unchanging from an external point of view.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] For example, an object that uses memoization to cache the results of expensive computations could still be considered an immutable object.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Strings and other concrete objects are typically expressed as immutable objects to improve readability and runtime efficiency in object-oriented programming.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Immutable objects are also useful because they are inherently thread-safe.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Other benefits are that they are simpler to understand and reason about and offer higher security than mutable objects.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In imperative programming, values held in program variables whose content never changes are known as *constants* to differentiate them from variables that could be altered during execution.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Examples include conversion factors from meters to feet, or the value of pi to several decimal places.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Read-only fields may be calculated when the program runs (unlike constants, which are known beforehand), but never change after they are initialized.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Sometimes, one talks of certain *fields* of an object being immutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] This means that there is no way to change those parts of the object state, even though other parts of the object may be changeable (*weakly immutable*).
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] If all fields are immutable, then the object is immutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] If the whole object cannot be extended by another class, the object is called *strongly immutable*.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] This might, for example, help to explicitly enforce certain invariants about certain data in the object staying the same through the lifetime of the object.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In some languages, this is done with a keyword (e.g.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] `const` in C++, `final` in Java) that designates the field as immutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Some languages reverse it: in OCaml, fields of an object or record are by default immutable, and must be explicitly marked with `mutable` to be so.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In most object-oriented languages, objects can be referred to using references.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Some examples of such languages are Java, C++, C#, VB.NET, and many scripting languages, such as Perl, Python, and Ruby.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In this case, it matters whether the state of an object can vary when objects are shared via references.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] If an object is known to be immutable, it is preferred to create a reference of it instead of copying the entire object.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] This is done to conserve memory by preventing data duplication and avoid calls to constructors and destructors; it also results in a potential boost in execution speed.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] The reference copying technique is much more difficult to use for mutable objects, because if any user of a mutable object reference changes it, all other users of that reference see the change.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] If this is not the intended effect, it can be difficult to notify the other users to have them respond correctly.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In these situations, defensive copying of the entire object rather than the reference is usually an easy but costly solution.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] The observer pattern is an alternative technique for handling changes to mutable objects.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] A technique that blends the advantages of **mutable** and **immutable** objects, and is supported directly in almost all modern hardware, is copy-on-write (COW).
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Using this technique, when a user asks the system to copy an object, it instead merely creates a new reference that still points to the same object.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] As soon as a user attempts to modify the object through a particular reference, the system makes a real copy, applies the modification to that, and sets the reference to refer to the new copy.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] The other users are unaffected, because they still refer to the original object.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Therefore, under COW, all users appear to have a mutable version of their objects, although in the case that users do not modify their objects, the space-saving and speed advantages of immutable objects are preserved.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Copy-on-write is popular in virtual memory systems because it allows them to save memory space while still correctly handling anything an application program might do.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] The practice of always using references in place of copies of equal objects is known as *interning*.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] If interning is used, two objects are considered equal if and only if their references, typically represented as pointers or integers, are equal.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Some languages do this automatically: for example, Python automatically interns short strings.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] If the algorithm that implements interning is guaranteed to do so in every case that it is possible, then comparing objects for equality is reduced to comparing their pointers – a substantial gain in speed in most applications.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] (Even if the algorithm is not guaranteed to be comprehensive, there still exists the possibility of a fast path case improvement when the objects are equal and use the same reference.) Interning is generally only useful for immutable objects.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Immutable objects can be useful in multi-threaded applications.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Multiple threads can act on data represented by immutable objects without concern of the data being changed by other threads.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Immutable objects are therefore considered more *thread-safe* than mutable objects.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Immutability does not imply that the object as stored in the computer's memory is unwriteable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Rather, immutability is a compile-time construct that indicates what a programmer can do through the normal interface of the object, not necessarily what they can absolutely do (for instance, by circumventing the type system or violating const correctness in C or C++).
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In Python, Java and the .NET Framework, strings are immutable objects.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Both Java and the .NET Framework have mutable versions of string.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In Java these are `StringBuffer` and `StringBuilder` (mutable versions of Java `String`) and in .NET this is `StringBuilder` (mutable version of .Net `String`).
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Python 3 has a mutable string (bytes) variant, named `bytearray`.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Additionally, all of the primitive wrapper classes in Java are immutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Similar patterns are the Immutable Interface and Immutable Wrapper.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In pure functional programming languages it is not possible to create mutable objects without extending the language (e.g. via a mutable references library or a foreign function interface), so all objects are immutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In Ada, any object is declared either *variable* (i.e. mutable; typically the implicit default), or `constant` (i.e. immutable) via the `constant` keyword.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Subprogram parameters are immutable in the *in* mode, and mutable in the *in out* and *out* modes.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In C# one can enforce immutability of the fields of a class with the `readonly` statement.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] By enforcing all the fields as immutable, the type becomes an immutable type.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In C++, a const-correct implementation of `ShoppingCart` would allow the user to create instances of the class and then use them as either `const` (immutable) or mutable, as desired, by providing two different versions of the `items()` method.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Note that, when there is a data member that is a pointer or reference to another object, then it is possible to mutate the object pointed to or referenced only within a non-const method.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] C++ also provides abstract (as opposed to bitwise) immutability via the `mutable` keyword, which lets a member variable be changed from within a `const` method.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In D, there exist two type qualifiers, `const` and `immutable`, for variables that cannot be changed.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Unlike C++'s `const`, Java's `final`, and C#'s `readonly`, they are transitive and recursively apply to anything reachable through references of such a variable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] The difference between `const` and `immutable` is what they apply to: `const` is a property of the variable: there might legally exist mutable references to referred value, i.e. the value can actually change.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In contrast, `immutable` is a property of the referred value: the value and anything transitively reachable from it cannot change (without breaking the type system, leading to undefined behavior).
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Any reference of that value must be marked `const` or `immutable`.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Basically for any unqualified type `T`, `const(T)` is the disjoint union of `T` (mutable) and `immutable(T)`.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] For a mutable `Example` object, its `mutableField` can be written to.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] For a `const(Example)` object, `mutableField` cannot be modified, it inherits `const`; `immutableField` is still immutable as it is the stronger guarantee.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] For an `immutable(Example)`, all fields are immutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Inside the braces, `c` might refer to the same object as `m`, so mutations to `m` could indirectly change `c` as well.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Also, `c` might refer to the same object as `i`, but since the value then is immutable, there are no changes.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] However, `m` and `i` cannot legally refer to the same object.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In the language of guarantees, mutable has no guarantees (the function might change the object), `const` is an outward-only guarantee that the function will not change anything, and `immutable` is a bidirectional guarantee (the function will not change the value and the caller must not change it).
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Values that are `const` or `immutable` must be initialized by direct assignment at the point of declaration or by a constructor.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Because `const` parameters forget if the value was mutable or not, a similar construct, `inout`, acts, in a sense, as a variable for mutability information.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] A function of type `const(S) function(const(T))` returns `const(S)` typed values for mutable, const and immutable arguments.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In contrast, a function of type `inout(S) function(inout(T))` returns `S` for mutable `T` arguments, `const(S)` for `const(T)` values, and `immutable(S)` for `immutable(T)` values.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Casting immutable values to mutable inflicts undefined behavior upon change, even if the original value comes from a mutable origin.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Casting mutable values to immutable can be legal when there remain no mutable references afterward.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] The type `string` is an alias for `immutable(char)[]`, i.e. a typed slice of memory of immutable characters.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Making substrings is cheap, as it just copies and modifies a pointer and a length filed, and safe, as the underlying data cannot be changed.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Objects of type `const(char)[]` can refer to strings, but also to mutable buffers.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Making a shallow copy of a const or immutable value removes the outer layer of immutability: Copying an immutable string (`immutable(char[])`) returns a string (`immutable(char)[]`).
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] The immutable pointer and length are being copied and the copies are mutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] The referred data has not been copied and keeps its qualifier, in the example `immutable`.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] It can be stripped by making a depper copy, e.g. using the `dup` function.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] The method `toLowerCase()` does not change the data "ABC" that `s` contains.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Instead, a new String object is instantiated and given the data "abc" during its construction.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] A reference to this String object is returned by the `toLowerCase()` method.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Now the String `s` references a new String object that contains "abc".
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] There is nothing in the syntax of the *declaration* of the class String that enforces it as immutable; rather, none of the String class's methods ever affect the data that a String object contains, thus making it immutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] The keyword `final` (detailed article) is used in implementing immutable primitive types and object references, but it cannot, by itself, make *the objects themselves* immutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Primitive type variables (`int`, `long`, `short`, etc.) can be reassigned after being defined.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Reference types cannot be made immutable just by using the `final` keyword.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Primitive wrappers (`Integer`, `Long`, `Short`, `Double`, `Float`, `Character`, `Byte`, `Boolean`) are also all immutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Immutable classes can be implemented by following a few simple guidelines.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In JavaScript, all primitive types (Undefined, Null, Boolean, Number, BigInt, String, Symbol) are immutable, but custom objects are generally mutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] To simulate immutability in an object, one may define properties as read-only (writable: false).
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] However, the approach above still lets new properties be added.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Alternatively, one may use Object.freeze to make existing objects immutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] With the implementation of ECMA262, JavaScript has the ability to create immutable references that cannot be reassigned.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] However, using a `const` declaration doesn't mean that value of the read-only reference is immutable, just that the name cannot be assigned to a new value.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] The use of immutable state has become a rising trend in JavaScript since the introduction of React, which favours Flux-like state management patterns such as Redux.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In PHP have readonly properties since version 8.1 and readonly classes since version 8.2.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In Python, some built-in types (numbers, Booleans, strings, tuples, frozensets) are immutable, but custom classes are generally mutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] The standard library helpers `collections.namedtuple` and `typing.NamedTuple`, available from Python 3.6 onward, create simple immutable classes.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Introduced in Python 3.7, `dataclasses` allow developers to emulate immutability with frozen instances.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] If a frozen dataclass is built, `dataclasses` will override `__setattr__()` and `__delattr__()` to raise `FrozenInstanceError` if invoked.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Racket substantially diverges from other Scheme implementations by making its core pair type ("cons cells") immutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Instead, it provides a parallel mutable pair type, via `mcons`, `mcar`, `set-mcar!` etc.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In addition, many immutable types are supported, for example, immutable strings and vectors, and these are used extensively.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] The language also supports immutable hash tables, implemented functionally, and immutable dictionaries.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Rust's ownership system allows developers to declare immutable variables, and pass immutable references.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] By default, all variables and references are immutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Mutable variables and references are explicitly created with the `mut` keyword.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Constant items in Rust are always immutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] In Scala, any entity (narrowly, a binding) can be defined as mutable or immutable: in the declaration, one can use `val` (value) for immutable entities and `var` (variable) for mutable ones.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] Note that even though an immutable binding can not be reassigned, it may still refer to a mutable object and it is still possible to call mutating methods on that object: the *binding* is immutable, but the underlying *object* may be mutable.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] defines an immutable entity `maxValue` (the integer type is inferred at compile-time) and a mutable entity named `currentValue`.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] By default, collection classes such as `List` and `Map` are immutable, so update-methods return a new instance rather than mutating an existing one.
[src:attrs-classes/immutable-object] While this may sound inefficient, the implementation of these classes and their guarantees of immutability mean that the new instance can re-use existing nodes, which, especially in the case of creating copies, is very efficient.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Notable languages with OOP support include Ada, ActionScript, C++, Common Lisp, C#, Dart, Eiffel, Fortran 2003, Haxe, Java, JavaScript, Kotlin, Logo, MATLAB, Objective-C, Object Pascal, Perl, PHP, Python, R, Raku, Ruby, Scala, SIMSCRIPT, Simula, Smalltalk, Swift, Vala and Visual Basic (.NET).
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] The idea of "objects" in programming began with the artificial intelligence group at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) in the late 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Here, "object" referred to LISP atoms with identified properties (attributes).
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Another early example was Sketchpad created by Ivan Sutherland at MIT in 1960–1961.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] In the glossary of his technical report, Sutherland defined terms like "object" and "instance" (with the class concept covered by "master" or "definition"), albeit specialized to graphical interaction.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Later, in 1968, AED-0, MIT's version of the ALGOL programming language, connected data structures ("plexes") and procedures, prefiguring what were later termed "messages", "methods", and "member functions".
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Topics such as data abstraction and modular programming were common points of discussion at this time.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Meanwhile, in Norway, Simula was developed during the years 1961–1967.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Simula introduced essential object-oriented ideas, such as classes, inheritance, and dynamic binding.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Simula was used mainly by researchers involved with physical modelling, like the movement of ships and their content through cargo ports.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Simula is generally accepted as being the first language with the primary features and framework of an object-oriented language.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Influenced by both MIT and Simula, Alan Kay began developing his own ideas in November 1966.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] He would go on to create Smalltalk, an influential OOP language.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] By 1967, Kay was already using the term "object-oriented programming" in conversation.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Although sometimes called the "father" of OOP, Kay has said his ideas differ from how OOP is commonly understood, and has implied that the computer science establishment did not adopt his notion.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] A 1976 MIT memo co-authored by Barbara Liskov lists Simula 67, CLU, and Alphard as object-oriented languages, but does not mention Smalltalk.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] In the 1970s, the first version of the Smalltalk programming language was developed at Xerox PARC by Alan Kay, Dan Ingalls and Adele Goldberg.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Smalltalk-72 was notable for use of objects at the language level and its graphical development environment.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Smalltalk was a fully dynamic system, allowing users to create and modify classes as they worked.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Much of the theory of OOP was developed in the context of Smalltalk, for example multiple inheritance.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] In the late 1970s and 1980s, OOP rose to prominence.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] The Flavors object-oriented Lisp was developed starting 1979, introducing multiple inheritance and mixins.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] In August 1981, Byte Magazine highlighted Smalltalk and OOP, introducing these ideas to a wide audience.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] LOOPS, the object system for Interlisp-D, was influenced by Smalltalk and Flavors, and a paper about it was published in 1982.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] In 1986, the first *Conference on Object-Oriented Programming, Systems, Languages, and Applications* (OOPSLA) was attended by 1,000 people.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] This conference marked the start of efforts to consolidate Lisp object systems, eventually resulting in the Common Lisp Object System.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] In the 1980s, there were a few attempts to design processor architectures that included hardware support for objects in memory, but these were not successful.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Examples include the Intel iAPX 432 and the Linn Smart Rekursiv.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] In the mid-1980s, new object-oriented languages like Objective-C, C++, and the Eiffel language emerged.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Objective-C was developed by Brad Cox, who had used Smalltalk at ITT Inc.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Bjarne Stroustrup created C++ based on his experience using Simula for his PhD thesis.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Bertrand Meyer produced the first design of the Eiffel language in 1985, which focused on software quality using a design by contract approach.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] In the 1990s, OOP became the main way of programming, especially as more languages supported it.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] These included Visual FoxPro 3.0, C++, and Delphi.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] OOP became even more popular with the rise of graphical user interfaces, which used objects for buttons, menus and other elements.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] One well-known example is Apple's Cocoa framework, used on macOS and written in Objective-C.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] OOP toolkits also enhanced the popularity of event-driven programming.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] At ETH Zürich, Niklaus Wirth and his colleagues created new approaches to OOP.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Modula-2 (1978) and Oberon (1987), included a distinctive approach to object orientation, classes, and type checking across module boundaries.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance is not obvious in Wirth's design since his nomenclature looks in the opposite direction: It is called type extension and the viewpoint is from the parent down to the inheritor.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Many programming languages that were initially developed before OOP was popular have been augmented with object-oriented features, including Ada, BASIC, Fortran, Pascal, and COBOL.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] The OOP features provided by languages vary.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Below are some common features of OOP languages.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Comparing OOP with other styles, like relational programming, is difficult because there isn't a clear, agreed-upon definition of OOP.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Some programming languages, like Java, provide information hiding via visibility key words (`private` and `public`).
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Some languages like Python don't provide a visibility feature, but developers might follow a convention such as starting a private member name with an underscore.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Intermediate levels of access also exist, such as Java's `protected` keyword, (which allows access from the same class and its subclasses, but not objects of a different class), and the `internal` keyword in C#, Swift, and Kotlin, which restricts access to files within the same module.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Supporters of information hiding and data abstraction say it makes code easier to reuse and intuitively represents real-world situations.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] However, others argue that OOP does not enhance readability or modularity.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Raymond has written that OOP languages tend to encourage thickly layered programs that destroy transparency.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Raymond compares this unfavourably to the approach taken with Unix and the C language.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] SOLID includes the open/closed principle, which says that classes and functions should be "open for extension, but closed for modification".
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Luca Cardelli has stated that OOP languages have "extremely poor modularity properties with respect to class extension and modification", and tend to be extremely complex.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Leo Brodie says that information hiding can lead to duplicate code, which goes against the don't repeat yourself rule of software development.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance can be supported via the class or the prototype, which have differences but use similar terms like object and instance.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] In class-based programming, the most common type of OOP, an object is an instance of a class.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] The class defines the data (variables) and methods (logic).
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] An object is created via the constructor.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Every instance of the class has the same set of variables and methods.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Classes may inherit from other classes, creating a hierarchy of classes: a case of a subclass inheriting from a super-class.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] For example, an `Employee` class might inherit from a `Person` class which endows the Employee object with the variables from `Person`.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] The subclass may add variables and methods that do not affect the super-class.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Most languages also allow the subclass to override super-class methods.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Some languages support multiple inheritance, where a class can inherit from more than one class, and other languages similarly support mixins or traits.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] For example, a mixin called UnicodeConversionMixin might add a method unicode_to_ascii() to both a FileReader and a WebPageScraper class.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] An abstract class cannot be directly instantiated as an object.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Other classes are utility classes which contain only class variables and methods and are not meant to be instantiated or subclassed.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Instead of providing a class concept, in prototype-based programming, an object is linked to another object, called its *prototype* or *parent*.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] In Self, an object may have multiple or no parents, but in the most popular prototype-based language, JavaScript, an object has exactly one prototype link, up to the base object whose prototype is null.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] A prototype acts as a model for new objects.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] For example, if you have an object `fruit`, you can make two objects `apple` and `orange` that share traits of the `fruit` prototype.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Prototype-based languages also allow objects to have their own unique properties, so the `apple` object might have an attribute `sugar_content`, while the `orange` or `fruit` objects do not.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] In all OOP languages, via object composition, an object can contain other objects.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] For example, an `Employee` object might contain an `Address` object, along with other information like `name` and `position`.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Composition is a "has-a" relationships, like "an employee has an address".
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Some languages, like Go, don't support inheritance.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Instead, they encourage "composition over inheritance", where objects are built using smaller parts instead of parent-child relationships.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] For example, instead of inheriting from class Person, the Employee class could simply contain a Person object.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] This lets the Employee class control how much of Person it exposes to other parts of the program.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Delegation is another language feature that can be used as an alternative to inheritance.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Programmers have different opinions on inheritance.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Bjarne Stroustrup, author of C++, has stated that it is possible to do OOP without inheritance.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Rob Pike has criticized inheritance for creating complex hierarchies instead of simpler solutions.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] People often think that if one class inherits from another, it means the subclass "is a" more specific version of the original class.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] This presumes the program semantics are that objects from the subclass can always replace objects from the original class without problems.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] This concept is known as behavioral subtyping, more specifically the Liskov substitution principle.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] However, this is often not true, especially in programming languages that allow mutable objects, objects that change after they are created.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] In fact, subtype polymorphism as enforced by the type checker in OOP languages cannot guarantee behavioral subtyping in most if not all contexts.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] For example, the circle-ellipse problem is notoriously difficult to handle using OOP's concept of inheritance.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Behavioral subtyping is undecidable in general, so it cannot be easily implemented by a compiler.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Because of this, programmers must carefully design class hierarchies to avoid mistakes that the programming language itself cannot catch.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] A method may be invoked via dynamic dispatch such that the method is selected at runtime instead of compile time.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] If the method choice depends on more than one type of object (such as other objects passed as parameters), it's called multiple dispatch.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] In this context, a method call is also known as message passing, meaning the method name and its inputs are like a message sent to the object for it to act on.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Dynamic dispatch works together with inheritance: if an object doesn't have the requested method, it looks up to its parent class (delegation), and continues up the chain to find a matching method.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Polymorphism in OOP refers to subtyping or subtype polymorphism, where a function can work with a specific interface and thus manipulate entities of different classes in a uniform manner.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] For example, imagine a program has two shapes: a circle and a square.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Both come from a common class called "Shape." Each shape has its own way of drawing itself.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] With subtype polymorphism, the program doesn't need to know the type of each shape, and can simply call the "Draw" method for each shape.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] The programming language runtime will ensure the correct version of the "Draw" method runs for each shape.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Because the details of each shape are handled inside their own classes, this makes the code simpler and more organized, enabling strong separation of concerns.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] An object's methods can access the object's data.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Many programming languages use a special word, like `this` or `self`, to refer to the current object.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] In languages that support open recursion, a method in an object can call other methods in the same object, including itself, using this special word.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] This allows a method in one class to call another method defined later in a subclass, a feature known as late binding.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Design patterns are common solutions to problems in software design.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Some design patterns are especially useful for OOP, and design patterns are typically introduced in an OOP context.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Sometimes, objects represent real-world things and processes in digital form.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] For example, a graphics program may have objects such as `circle`, `square`, and `menu`.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] An online shopping system might have objects such as `shopping cart`, `customer`, and `product`.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Niklaus Wirth said, "This paradigm [OOP] closely reflects the structure of systems in the real world and is therefore well suited to model complex systems with complex behavior".
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] However, more often, objects represent abstract entities, like an open file or a unit converter.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Not everyone agrees that OOP makes it easy to copy the real world exactly or that doing so is even necessary.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Bob Martin suggests that because classes are software, their relationships don't match the real-world relationships they represent.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Bertrand Meyer argues that a program is not a model of the world but a model of some part of the world; "Reality is a cousin twice removed".
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Steve Yegge noted that natural languages lack the OOP approach of naming a thing (object) before an action (method), as opposed to functional programming which does the reverse.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] This can make an OOP solution more complex than one written via procedural programming.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] The following are notable software design patterns for OOP objects.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] A common anti-pattern is the God object, an object that knows or does too much.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Both OOP and relational database management systems (RDBMSs) are widely used in software today.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] However, relational databases don't store objects directly, which creates a challenge when using them together.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] This issue is called object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] To solve this problem, developers use different methods, but none of them are perfect.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] One of the most common solutions is object-relational mapping (ORM), which helps connect object-oriented programs to relational databases.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Examples of ORM tools include Visual FoxPro, Java Data Objects, and Ruby on Rails ActiveRecord.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Some databases, called object databases, are designed to work with OOP.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] However, they have not been as popular or successful as relational databases.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Date and Darwen have proposed a theoretical foundation that uses OOP as a kind of customizable type system to support RDBMSs, but it forbids objects containing pointers to other objects.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] In responsibility-driven design, classes are built around what they need to do and the information they share, in the form of a contract.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] This is different from data-driven design, where classes are built based on the data they need to store.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] According to Wirfs-Brock and Wilkerson, the originators of responsibility-driven design, responsibility-driven design is the better approach.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Researchers have tried to formally define the semantics of OOP.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance presents difficulties, particularly with the interactions between open recursion and encapsulated state.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Researchers have used recursive types and co-algebraic data types to incorporate essential features of OOP.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Abadi and Cardelli defined several extensions of System F<: that deal with mutable objects, allowing both subtype polymorphism and parametric polymorphism (generics), and were able to formally model many OOP concepts and constructs.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Although far from trivial, static analysis of object-oriented programming languages such as Java is a mature field, with several commercial tools.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Many popular programming languages, like C++, Java, and Python, use OOP.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] In the past, OOP was widely accepted, but recently, some programmers have criticized it and prefer functional programming instead.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] A study by Potok et al. found no major difference in productivity between OOP and procedural programming.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Some believe that OOP places too much focus on using objects rather than on algorithms and data structures.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] For example, programmer Rob Pike pointed out that OOP can make programmers think more about type hierarchy than composition.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] He has called OOP "the Roman numerals of computing".
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Rich Hickey, creator of Clojure, described OOP as overly simplistic, especially when it comes to representing real-world things that change over time.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Alexander Stepanov said that OOP tries to fit everything into a single type, which can be limiting.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] He argued that sometimes we need multisorted algebras: families of interfaces that span multiple types, such as in generic programming.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Stepanov also said that calling everything an "object" doesn't add much understanding.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] OOP was created to make code easier to reuse and maintain.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] However, it was not designed to clearly show the flow of a program's instructions.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] As computers began using more parallel processing and multiple threads, it became more important to understand and control how instructions flow.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Paul Graham believes big companies like OOP because it helps manage large teams of average programmers.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] He argues that OOP adds structure, making it harder for one person to make serious mistakes, but at the same time restrains smart programmers.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Raymond, a Unix programmer and open-source software advocate, argues that OOP is not the best way to write programs.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Richard Feldman says that, while OOP features helped some languages stay organized, their popularity comes from other reasons.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Lawrence Krubner argues that OOP doesn't offer special advantages compared to other styles, like functional programming, and can complicate coding.
[src:attrs-classes/object-oriented-programming] Luca Cardelli says that OOP is slower and takes longer to compile than procedural programming.
[src:attrs-classes/why] If you’d like third party’s account why *attrs* is great, have a look at Glyph’s *The One Python Library Everyone Needs*.
[src:attrs-classes/why] It predates type annotations and hence Data Classes, but it masterfully illustrates the appeal of class-building packages.
[src:attrs-classes/why] They are the result of the Python community’s wish to have an easier way to write classes in the standard library that doesn’t carry the problems of `namedtuple`s.
[src:attrs-classes/why] To that end, *attrs* and its developers were involved in the PEP process and while we may disagree with some minor decisions that have been made, it’s a fine library and if it stops you from abusing `namedtuple`s, they are a huge win.
[src:attrs-classes/why] Nevertheless, there are still reasons to prefer *attrs* over Data Classes.
[src:attrs-classes/why] One way to think about *attrs* vs Data Classes is that *attrs* is a fully-fledged toolkit to write powerful classes while Data Classes are an easy way to get a class with some attributes.
[src:attrs-classes/why] Pydantic is first and foremost a *data validation & type coercion library*.
[src:attrs-classes/why] As such, it is a capable complement to class building libraries like *attrs* (or Data Classes!) for parsing and validating untrusted data.
[src:attrs-classes/why] However, as convenient as it might be, using it for your business or domain layer is problematic in several ways: Is it really necessary to re-validate all your objects while reading them from a trusted database?
[src:attrs-classes/why] Should the shape of your web API really apply design pressure on your business objects and therefore business code?
[src:attrs-classes/why] In the parlance of *Form, Command, and Model Validation*, Pydantic is the right tool for *Commands*.
[src:attrs-classes/why] `collections.namedtuple`s are tuples with names, not classes.[1] Since writing classes is tiresome in Python, every now and then someone discovers all the typing they could save and gets really excited.
[src:attrs-classes/why] However, that convenience comes at a price.
[src:attrs-classes/why] All these things make `namedtuple`s a particularly poor choice for public APIs because all your objects are irrevocably tainted.
[src:attrs-classes/why] With *attrs* your users won’t notice a difference because it creates regular, well-behaved classes.
[src:attrs-classes/why] If you want a *tuple with names*, by all means: go for a `namedtuple`.[5] But if you want a class with methods, you’re doing yourself a disservice by relying on a pile of hacks that requires you to employ even more hacks as your requirements expand.
[src:attrs-classes/why] Other than that, *attrs* also adds nifty features like validators, converters, and (mutable!) default values.
[src:attrs-classes/why] Why would you want to write `customer[2]` instead of `customer.first_name`?
[src:attrs-classes/why] Don’t get me started when you add nesting.
[src:attrs-classes/why] If you’ve never run into mysterious tuples you had no idea what the hell they meant while debugging, you’re much smarter than yours truly.
[src:attrs-classes/why] Using proper classes with names and types makes program code much more readable and comprehensible.
[src:attrs-classes/why] Especially when trying to grok a new piece of software or returning to old code after several months.
[src:attrs-classes/why] Imagine you have a function that takes or returns a tuple.
[src:attrs-classes/why] Especially if you use tuple unpacking (eg.
[src:attrs-classes/why] `x, y = get_point()`), adding additional data means that you have to change the invocation of that function *everywhere*.
[src:attrs-classes/why] Adding an attribute to a class concerns only those who actually care about that attribute.
[src:attrs-classes/why] If you have a dict, it maps something to something else.
[src:attrs-classes/why] You should be able to add and remove values.
[src:attrs-classes/why] In other words: if your dict has a fixed and known set of keys, it is an object, not a hash.
[src:attrs-classes/why] So if you never iterate over the keys of a dict, you should use a proper class.
[src:attrs-classes/why] While we’re fans of all things artisanal, writing the same nine methods again and again doesn’t qualify.
[src:attrs-classes/why] I usually manage to get some typos inside and there’s simply more code that can break and thus has to be tested.
[src:attrs-classes/why] That’s quite a mouthful and it doesn’t even use any of *attrs*’s more advanced features like validators or default values.
[src:attrs-classes/why] And who will guarantee you, that you don’t accidentally flip the `<` in your tenth implementation of `__gt__`?
[src:attrs-classes/why] *attrs* will also do the right thing around hashing: It will write a `__hash__` for you if your class should be hashable and marks your class as unhashable if not.
[src:attrs-classes/why] It also should be noted that *attrs* is not an all-or-nothing solution.
[src:attrs-classes/why] If you don’t care and like the sound of your mechanical keyboard, we’re not gonna stop you.
[src:attrs-classes/why] However it takes a lot of bias and determined rationalization to claim that *attrs* raises the mental burden on a project given how difficult it is to find the important bits in a hand-written class and how annoying it is to ensure you’ve copy-pasted your code correctly over all your classes.
[src:attrs-classes/why] In any case, if you ever get sick of the repetitiveness and the drowning of important code in a sea of boilerplate, *attrs* will be waiting for you.
